page.title: 16Woodland 1
page.content: The ecology of the area is greatly influenced by the abundance of woodland in the western half and the lack of it in the eastern section.Deciduous woodland particularly contains a wide variety of insects,birds and some parasitic plants,all benefitting from the less densely packed foliage of broad-leaved trees.In the western half, beech was the most dominant hardwood. Ash and sycamore were also in abundance often growing along roadsides.Willows & a few very young elms bordered much of the R.Churn.In the south west,the woodland was virtually all deciduous, but further north mixed coniferous and deciduous predominated.On the plateau area to the east woodland was very sparse,some oaks were found in small sheltered valleys & stunted hawthorn bordered the field boundaries.
